To anchor the resolution in unassailable democratic and international-law logic, borrow the three pillars that already enjoy universal acceptance: (1) the equal-rights/sovereignty principle in the UN Charter; (2) the “self-determination of peoples” rule common to both UN and human-rights treaties; and (3) the democratic-governance standard the UN itself now uses to judge the legitimacy of any political order.  
The draft therefore does not “declare” independence; it simply records that, under existing law, only the population on Taiwan can legitimately decide its future and that any attempt to coerce that population would violate peremptory norms.  That keeps the text inside the legal space every UN member already concedes, while still sounding ironclad.

—————————————————————
DRAFT RESOLUTION  
Affirming the Democratic Right of the People of Taiwan to Determine Their Own Political Status

The [House/Senate/Parliament]—

Recalling that the Charter of the United Nations, in Article 1(2) and Article 55, establishes the equal rights and self-determination of peoples as one of the Organization’s foundational purposes;

Reaffirming the Friendly Relations Declaration (GA Res. 2625/XXV), which prohibits the use or threat of force against the territorial integrity or political independence of any State and confirms that the territory of a people shall not be the object of forcible acquisition by another State;

Reaffirming further the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which guarantee every people the right freely to choose their political status without external coercion;

Noting that the International Court of Justice, in the Kosovo Advisory Opinion (2010), held that a people exercising their internal self-government through democratic institutions enjoy the constitutional authority to express a will on their final status;

Recognizing that the people of Taiwan have, over more than three decades, built robust democratic institutions that meet the UN’s own benchmarks for legitimate, participatory, and pluralistic governance;

Convinced that democratic legitimacy is the sole source of sovereign authority in the 21st century and that any claim of sovereignty over a population that has not freely consented to it is incompatible with contemporary international law;

Declares that:

1. The final political status of Taiwan must be determined peacefully and democratically by the people resident on Taiwan, in accordance with their freely expressed will;

2. Any attempt to alter that status by force, threat of force, economic coercion, or disinformation campaigns would violate Article 2(4) of the UN Charter, customary international law, and the peremptory norm prohibiting aggression;

3. The United States [or “this House”] will regard the outcome of any future, genuine, and inclusive referendum or electoral process conducted under Taiwan’s existing constitutional order as the sole democratic basis for any change or continuity in Taiwan’s international status;

4. The United States will continue to support, consistent with the Taiwan Relations Act and the Six Assurances, Taiwan’s meaningful participation in international fora that affect the rights and interests of its people, because their exclusion frustrates the very self-determination principle endorsed by every member of the United Nations.

—————————————————————

Key drafting choices

- “Must be determined … by the people resident on Taiwan” = a direct invocation of self-determination without pronouncing on whether that leads to independence, federation, confederation, or continued autonomy.  
- Citing GA Res. 2625 and ICJ Kosovo turns the resolution into a restatement of existing law, not a new policy invention.  
- “Would violate Article 2(4)…peremptory norm” triggers the language of jus cogens—the strongest stratum of international law—giving the text legal, not merely political, bite.  
- The last clause keeps you inside “one-China” diplomatic ambiguity while still locking the ultimate legitimacy key in the hands of Taiwan’s electorate.
